A
(pts)
= ("Data Starters Who Initiate %") * Data Sankey Scalar
Description: For the Sankey - reporting out the base case value for the total number of patients in the cohort who meet the criteria defining this state.
Present in 1 view:
  • UI Outputs
Used by:
  • This is a supplementary variable.
Used by:
  • "Data Appointment Supply (75th percentile)" - The number of appointments available with this team for each service each week. The estimate is calculated using the volume of visits completed each week with the team in each service over one year. (appt/wk)
  • "Data Completers Who Graduate %" - Of patients who complete eight or more psychotherapy visits within their first three months (i.e., completers), this is the proportion who do not return for any more psychotherapy visits after three months (i.e., patients who graduate). (pct)
  • Data First Visit RVI - Set to 1 wk, because everyone gets their first appointment in their first week in care.
  • Data Initiators Coming Back Later RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • "Data Initiators Who Complete %" - Of patients who complete at least two to seven psychotherapy visits within three months (i.e., initiators), this is the proportion of patients who complete eight or more psychotherapy visits within three months (i.e., patients who complete a timely dose). (pct)
  • Data Initiators Who Complete RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data Initiators Who Graduate Duration - Median engagement time estimated from the team's own data for patients in their 2-7th visit, who will go on to 8 or more visits in the first three months.
  • "Data Initiators Who Quit Early %" - Of patients who complete at least two to seven psychotherapy visits within their first three months (i.e., initiators), this is the proportion of patients who never complete another psychotherapy visit with this team (i.e., patients who quit before completing a timely dose). (pct)
  • Data Initiators Who Quit Early Duration - Median engagement time estimated from the team's own data for patients in their 2-7th visit, who will not continue care after the first three months.
  • Data Initiators Who Quit Early RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data New Patient Start Rate - From the team's data: psycho60 visits/appts for new patients per wk.
  • Data Sankey Scalar - The total number of patients in the cohort defined by the team's data.
  • "Data Starters Who Initiate %" - Of patients who complete at least one psythotherapy visit within their first three months (i.e., starters), this is the proportion who return for at least two to seven psychotherapy visits within their first three months (i.e., patients who initiate treatment). (pct)
  • Data Starters Who Return High RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • "Data Starters Who Return Later %" - Of patients who complete at least one psythotherapy visit within their first three months (i.e., starters), this is the proportion who do not complete any more psychotherapy visits within three months, but return for at least one more psychotherapy visit after three months ((i.e., patients who return later). (pct)
  • Data Starters Who Return Low RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data Starters Who Return Medium RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).

A
(appt/wk)
= IF THEN ELSE(User Appointment Supply<0,"Data Appointment Supply (75th percentile)",IF THEN ELSE(Time<Experiment wk, "Data Appointment Supply (75th percentile)", User Appointment Supply))
Description: Total number of 60 minute Psychotherapy appointments offered by the team each wk.
Present in 1 view:
  • Supply Used
Used by:
  • Appointments Available for New Patients - All remaining supply, after all existing patients are seen. Users can also set aside additional appointments specifically for new patients, which allows the team to start more patients (i.e., they receive a first visit) than they can initiate (i.e., they receive a second visit). It is prevented from going below zero.
  • Appointments for Existing Patients - The number of appointments used by existing patients each week. The team either satisfies all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or uses all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply), leaving no appointments available for new patients. (appt/wk)
  • Completing Rate - Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)
  • Supply Available for New Pts who can start 2nd visit - All remaining supply, after all existing patients are seen and taking new patient carve-outs into account. It is prevented from going below zero.
Default psy i v21 2022 02 11.2

F,A

(appt/wk)
= Appointment Supply
Description: Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)
Present in 1 view:
  • Supply Used
Used by:
  • Appointments in Psychotherapy - The total number of appointments for psychotherapy on the calendar. (appts)
  • Ballpark Initial Appointments in Psychotherapy - The number of appointments on the calendar is not a meaningful measure of the system, so accuracy here is not necessary.

  • Bars E9 - For calculating "Sankey bar heights" - The total number of visits for the average time in treatment after their first three months in care (i.e., the product of the frequency of visits and their total time in treatment) of patient who completed only 1 visit in their first 3 months (i.e., "Completer" patients who receive even more visits).
  • "Data Appointment Supply (75th percentile)" - The number of appointments available with this team for each service each week. The estimate is calculated using the volume of visits completed each week with the team in each service over one year. (appt/wk)
  • "Data AUD within 3 months %" - An estimate of the proportion of the team's patients with alchohol use disorder (AUD), calculated from the cohort of patients who completed visits charted with a primary diagnosis of AUD within their entire psychotherapy engagement. (pct)
  • Data Completer Who Return Later High Duration - The median of the upper quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 2-7 visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • Data Completer Who Return Later Low Duration - The median of the lower quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 8 or more visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • Data Completer Who Return Later Medium Duration - The median of the inner two quartiles of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 8 or more visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "Data Completers Who Graduate %" - Of patients who complete eight or more psychotherapy visits within their first three months (i.e., completers), this is the proportion who do not return for any more psychotherapy visits after three months (i.e., patients who graduate). (pct)
  • Data Completers Who Return High RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data Completers Who Return Low RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data Completers Who Return Medium RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • "Data DEP within 3 months %" - An estimate of the proportion of the team's patients with depression (DEP), calculated from the cohort of patients who completed visits charted with a primary diagnosis of DEP within their entire psychotherapy engagement. (pct)
  • Data First Visit RVI - Set to 1 wk, because everyone gets their first appointment in their first week in care.
  • Data Initiators Coming Back Later RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • "Data Initiators Who Complete %" - Of patients who complete at least two to seven psychotherapy visits within three months (i.e., initiators), this is the proportion of patients who complete eight or more psychotherapy visits within three months (i.e., patients who complete a timely dose). (pct)
  • Data Initiators Who Complete RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data Initiators Who Graduate Duration - Median engagement time estimated from the team's own data for patients in their 2-7th visit, who will go on to 8 or more visits in the first three months.
  • "Data Initiators Who Quit Early %" - Of patients who complete at least two to seven psychotherapy visits within their first three months (i.e., initiators), this is the proportion of patients who never complete another psychotherapy visit with this team (i.e., patients who quit before completing a timely dose). (pct)
  • Data Initiators Who Quit Early Duration - Median engagement time estimated from the team's own data for patients in their 2-7th visit, who will not continue care after the first three months.
  • Data Initiators Who Quit Early RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data Initiators Who Return High RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data Initiators Who Return Later High Duration - The median of the upper quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 2-7 visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • Data Initiators Who Return Later Low Duration - The median of the lower quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 2-7 visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • Data Initiators Who Return Later Medium Duration - The median of the inner two quartiles of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 2-7 visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • Data Initiators Who Return Low RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data Initiators Who Return Medium RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • Data New Patient Start Rate - From the team's data: psycho60 visits/appts for new patients per wk.
  • "Data OUD within 3 months %" - An estimate of the proportion of the team's patients with opioid use disorder (OUD), calculated from the cohort of patients who completed visits charted with a primary diagnosis of OUD within their entire psychotherapy engagement. (pct)
  • "Data PTSD within 3 months %" - An estimate of the proportion of the team's patients with post traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), calculated from the cohort of patients who completed visits charted with a primary diagnosis of PTSD within their entire psychotherapy engagement. (pct)
  • Data Sankey Scalar - The total number of patients in the cohort defined by the team's data.
  • "Data Starters Who Initiate %" - Of patients who complete at least one psythotherapy visit within their first three months (i.e., starters), this is the proportion who return for at least two to seven psychotherapy visits within their first three months (i.e., patients who initiate treatment). (pct)
  • Data Starters Who Return High RVI - The average number of weeks between visits, estimated from the mean of all individual patients' counts of completed appointments that meet the time criteria defining this stock and their time to complete that subset of their appointments (i.e., the date difference between their last completed appointment and their first).
  • "Data Starters Who Return Later %" - Of patients who complete at least one psythotherapy visit within their first three months (i.e., starters), this is the proportion who do not complete any more psychotherapy visits within three months, but return for at least one more psychotherapy visit after three months ((i.e., patients who return later). (pct)

G
(Dmnl [0,1,1])
= GAME (0)
Description: Initiate an "Intensive Outpatient Program" for new patients, where they are seen twice as often for half as many weeks after they initiate care. Estimates from the team's data for Return Visit Interval and Median Engagement Duration during a patient's first 3 months in care are modified accordingly. Also, this more intensive therapy results in more patients completing a timely dose, modifying patient flow percentages estimated from the team's data (specifically: the gap between the desired and current state for "Starters who Initiate %," "Initiators who Complete %," and "Completers who Graduate %" all increase by 30%, while the gap between the desired and current state for "Initiators who Quit Early %" is reduced by 30%). These changes do not affect patient care patterns for patients who remain in care after completing their timely dose of psychotherapy. A team can choose to "Partially" or "Fully" implement the IOP, where "Partial" indicates that only half their patients follow the IOP, and "Fully" indicates that all new patients follow the IOP. (pct)
Present in 2 views:
  • Supply Used
  • Psychotherapy Service
Used by:
  • "Effect of Implement IOP on Completer %" - The relative change for new patients following care pathways after initiating an Intensive Outpatient Program, starting in Week zero, delayed by the average time it takes to get to completion (now, with IOP is 6 weeks, instead of the usual 12 weeks).
  • Effect of Implement IOP on Durations - The relative change in patients' engagement durations after they initiate care caused by implementing an Intensive Outpatient Program.
  • Effect of Implement IOP on Frequency - The relative change in patients' visit frequency after they initiate care caused by implementing an Intensive Outpatient Program. Note, if these two percentages sum to 100%, that implies that no (zero percent) Starters are quitting early (i.e., the team has no "One-and-Dones"). (pct)

  • Psychotherapy Service
Used by:
  • "Actual Starters Who Initiate %" - Constrained to be between 0 and 100%.
Default psy i v21 2022 02 11.2
(Default)		 #306
G
(Dmnl [-1,1,0.05])
= GAME (-0.05)
Description: This slider controls the proportion of patients who, after starting psychotherapy, then fail to initiate in a timely manner (i.e., who never complete another visit in their first three months, but do complete more visits later). This replaces the base case value estimated from the team's data. This value, plus the value of "Starters who Initiate %" should not sum to more than 100%, otherwise patients will be pursuing multiple engagement pathways simultaneously. Note, if these two percentages sum to 100%, that implies that no (zero percent) Starters are quitting early (i.e., the team has no "One-and-Dones"). (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Psychotherapy Service
Used by:
  • "Actual Starters Who Return Later %" - The percent of patients who return for more appointments in the subsequent three months after completing only one visit in their first three months. The percent of these "One-n-More Laters" is constrained between 0 and 100%.

Level Structure †

"<3mo Visit 1 who can start 2" = ∫Starting Rate who can Initiate-Ending who can Initiate dt + [0]
    Ending who can Initiate = "<3mo Visit 1 who can start 2"/Median Time in Visit 1
    Starting Rate who can Initiate = Starting Psychotherapy who can start 2

Appointments in Psychotherapy = ∫Booking Rate-Completing Rate dt + [Ballpark Initial Appointments in Psychotherapy]
Ballpark Initial Appointments in Psychotherapy = Completing Rate * "Avg RVI >3mo"
    Booking Rate = Appointments Available for New Patients+Appointments for Existing Patients
    Completing Rate = Appointment Supply

Completers Patients in over 7 Visits = ∫Completion Rate-Ending After 8 or More Visits Rate dt + [0]
    Completion Rate = Continuting on to Visit 8 Rate
    Ending After 8 or More Visits Rate = MAX(ZIDZ(Completers Patients in over 7 Visits, ("ET - Completers who Graduate"*Effect of Implement IOP on Durations)),0)

"From Completers-HighD" = ∫From Completers into High D-From Completers Ending High D dt + [0]
    From Completers Ending High D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Completers-HighD", "Engagement Time - From 8 or More Visits (4th Quartile)"),0)
    From Completers into High D = Completers Continuing Treatment Rate after 3 Months*"Starting HighD %"

"From Completers-LowD" = ∫From Completers into Low D-From Completers Ending Low D dt + [0]
    From Completers Ending Low D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Completers-LowD", "Engagement Time - From 8 or More Visits (1st Quartile)"),0)
    From Completers into Low D = Completers Continuing Treatment Rate after 3 Months*"Starting LowD %"

"From Completers-MidD" = ∫From Completers into Mid D-From Completers Ending Mid D dt + [0]
    From Completers Ending Mid D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Completers-MidD", "Engagement Time - From 8 or More Visits (Mean)"),0)
    From Completers into Mid D = Completers Continuing Treatment Rate after 3 Months*"Starting MidD %"

"From Initiators-HighD" = ∫From Initiators into High D-From Initiators Ending High D dt + [0]
    From Initiators Ending High D = MAX(ZIDZ( "From Initiators-HighD", "Engagement Time - From 2 to 7 Visits (4th Quartile)"),0)
    From Initiators into High D = Initiators Continue Treatment Rate after 3 Months*"Starting HighD %"

"From Initiators-LowD" = ∫From Initiators into Low D-From Initiators Ending Low D dt + [0]
    From Initiators Ending Low D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Initiators-LowD", "Engagement Time - From 2 to 7 Visits (1st Quartile)"),0)
    From Initiators into Low D = Initiators Continue Treatment Rate after 3 Months*"Starting LowD %"

"From Initiators-MidD" = ∫From Initiators into Mid D-From Initiators Ending Mid D dt + [0]
    From Initiators Ending Mid D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Initiators-MidD", "Engagement Time - From 2 to 7 Visits (Mean)"),0)
    From Initiators into Mid D = Initiators Continue Treatment Rate after 3 Months*"Starting MidD %"

"From Starters-HighD" = ∫From Starters into High D-From Starters Ending High D dt + [0]
    From Starters Ending High D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Starters-HighD", "Engagement Time - From 1 Visit (4th Quartile)"),0)
    From Starters into High D = Starters Continue Treatment Rate after 3 Months*"Starting HighD %"

"From Starters-LowD" = ∫From Starters into Low D-From Starters Ending Low D dt + [0]
    From Starters Ending Low D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Starters-LowD", "Engagement Time - From 1 Visit (1st Quartile)"),0)
    From Starters into Low D = Starters Continue Treatment Rate after 3 Months*"Starting LowD %"

"From Starters-MidD" = ∫From Starters into Mid D-From Starters Ending Mid D dt + [0]
    From Starters Ending Mid D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Starters-MidD", "Engagement Time - From 1 Visit (Mean)"),0)
    From Starters into Mid D = Starters Continue Treatment Rate after 3 Months*"Starting MidD %"

Initiators Who Will Continue = ∫Initiation Rate who will Complete-Continuting on to Visit 8 Rate dt + [0]
    Continuting on to Visit 8 Rate = MAX(ZIDZ(Initiators Who Will Continue, (Data Initiators Who Graduate Duration*Effect of Implement IOP on Durations)),0)
    Initiation Rate who will Complete = Ending who can Initiate*"Actual Starters who Initiate % including any IOP Effect"*"Actual Initiators who Complete % including IOP Effect"

Initiators Who Will Quit = ∫Initiation Rate who will Quit-Ending During Visit 2 to 7 Rate dt + [0]
    Ending During Visit 2 to 7 Rate = MAX(ZIDZ(Initiators Who Will Quit, (Data Initiators Who Quit Early Duration*Effect of Implement IOP on Durations)),0)
    Initiation Rate who will Quit = Ending who can Initiate*"Actual Starters who Initiate % including any IOP Effect"*"Actual Initiators Who Quit Early % including any IOP Effect"

Initiators Who Will Return = ∫Initation Rate who will Return-Initiators Continue Treatment Rate after 3 Months dt + [0]
    Initation Rate who will Return = Ending who can Initiate*"Actual Starters who Initiate % including any IOP Effect"*(1-"Actual Initiators who Complete % including IOP Effect"-"Actual Initiators Who Quit Early % including any IOP Effect")
    Initiators Continue Treatment Rate after 3 Months = MAX(Initiators Who Will Return/("ET - Initiators Who Return"*Effect of Implement IOP on Durations),0)

Starters Patients in First Visit = ∫Starting Rate-Ending First Visit dt + [0]
    Ending First Visit = Starters Patients in First Visit/Median Time in Visit 1
    Starting Rate = Starting Psychotherapy

†  Level Structure Report still under development.
